07005nam a22008175i 9780857453662DE-B159720221004111318.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||221004t20072007nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808574536627 a10.1515/97808574536622doi  a(DE-B1597)636314  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHQ1587b.W664 2010 7aSOC0070002bisacsh04a304.8208209422300aWomen Migrants From East to West :bGender, Mobility and Belonging in Contemporary Europe /ced. by uisa, Dawn Lyon, Enrica Capussotti, Ioanna Laliotou. 1aNew York; aOxford : bBerghahn Books, c[2007] 4c©2007  a1 online resource (344 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgements -- tEditors’ Introduction -- tPart I Subjectivity, Mobility and Gender in Europe -- tChapter 1 On Becoming Europeans -- tChapter 2 ‘I want to see the world’: Mobility and Subjectivity in the European Context -- tChapter 3 Transformations of Legal Subjectivity in Europe: From the Subjection of Women to Privileged Subjects -- tIntermezzo ‘A Dance through Life’: Narratives of Migrant Women -- tPart II Subjectivity in Motion: Analysing the Lives of Migrant Women -- tChapter 4 Imaginary Geographies: Border-places and ‘Home’ in the Narratives of Migrant Women -- tChapter 5 ‘My hobby is people’: Migration and Communication in the Light of Late Totalitarianism -- tChapter 6 Migrant Women in Work -- tChapter 7 The Topos of Love in the Life-stories of Migrant Women -- tChapter 8 Food-talk: Markers of Identity and Imaginary Belongings -- tIntermezzo Relationships in the Making: Accounts of Native Women -- tPart III: Processes of Identification: Inclusion and Exclusion of Migrant Women -- tChapter 9 Migration, Integration and Emancipation: Women’s Positioning in the Debate in the Netherlands -- tChapter 10 Modernity versus Backwardness: Italian Women’s Perceptions of Self and Other -- tChapter 11 Moral and Cultural Boundaries in Representations of Migrants: Italy and the Netherlands in Comparative Perspective -- tChapter 12 Changing Matrimonial Law in the Image of Immigration Law -- tIntermezzo In Transit: Space, People, Identities -- tConclusions Gender, Subjectivity, Europe: A Constellation for the Future -- tAppendix 1 Summary of individual interviewees -- tAppendix 2 Summary of interviewees’ characteristics by nationality -- tNotes on Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBased on the oral histories of eighty migrant women and thirty additional interviews with ‘native’ women in the ‘receiving’ countries, this volume documents the contemporary phenomenon of the feminisation of migration through an exploration of the lives of women, who have moved from Bulgaria and Hungary to Italy and the Netherlands. It assumes migrants to be active subjects, creating possibilities and taking decisions in their own lives, as well as being subject to legal and political regulation, and the book analyses the new forms of subjectivity that come about through mobility. Part I is a largely conceptual exploration of subjectivity, mobility and gender in Europe. The chapters in Part II focus on love, work, home, communication, and food, themes which emerged from the migrant women’s accounts. In Part III, based on the interviews with ‘native’ women – employers, friends, or in associations relevant to migrant women – the chapters analyse their representations of migrants, and the book goes on to explore forms of intersubjectivity between European women of different cultural origins. A major contribution of this book is to consider how the movement of people across Europe is changing the cultural and social landscape with implications for how we think about what Europe means. Cover image: Painting by Carla Accardi. Reproduced with the kind permission of Luca Barsi of the Galleria Accademia, Via Accademia Albertina 3/e, 10123 Torino.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 04. Okt 2022) 0aEast EuropeanszEurope, WesternxSocial conditions. 0aWomen immigrantszEuropexSocial conditions. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Emigration & Immigration.2bisacsh1 aAlexandrova, Nadejda, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBraidotti, Rosi, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCapussotti, Enrica, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCapussotti, Enrica, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aConradsen, Inger Marie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHortobagyi, Anna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKronborg, Annette, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLaliotou, Ioanna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLaliotou, Ioanna, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aLyon, Dawn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLyon, Dawn, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aNikolchina, Miglena, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPasserini, Luisa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPetersen, Hanne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aPeto, Andrea, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVonk, Esther, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 auisa, , eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt40uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978085745366240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780857453662423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780857453662/original  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aE